ibution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":1,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705182,"age":32,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":52,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":62,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705185,"age":72,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Francis was born in 1034, in England. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Willielmus de Peverell."},"et":{"1034–":"1034–Surnud","1034–Male":"1034–Surnud","1047–1131":"1047–1131","1067–1136":"1067–1136","1080–1133":"1080–1133","1034–Female":"1034–Surnud","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1106":"1106","1136":"1136","1047":"1047","Abt 1067":"umbes 1067","1035":"1035","1034":"1034","1133":"1133","1067":"1067","Abt 1080":"umbes 1080","Of Suffolk,Eng":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bourn, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bourn, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Brunne, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"1034–":"1034–Kuollut","1034–Male":"1034–Kuollut","1047–1131":"1047–1131","1067–1136":"1067–1136","1080–1133":"1080–1133","1034–Female":"1034–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1